{% apply highlight_blocks %}
<article class="docs-content">
    <h1>Comparisons</h1>
    <p>
        How does php-via compare to other frameworks in the <a href="https://data-star.dev/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Datastar</a> ecosystem?
        This page summarises the key trade-offs against two peers: <strong>Datapages</strong> (Go) and <strong>Stario</strong> (Python).
    </p>

    <h2 id="datapages">php-via vs Datapages</h2>
    <p>
        <a href="https://datapages.dev" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Datapages</a> (v0.2.1) is a Go + Templ + Datastar
        <em>code-generation</em> framework. It parses your Go source and generates routing, SSE glue, auth, CSRF, and URL helpers.
    </p>

    <table style="width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:var(--font-size-0); margin-block:var(--size-5);">
        <thead>
            <tr style="border-block-end:2px solid var(--border);">
                <th style="text-align:left; padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Area</th>
                <th style="text-align:left; padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Datapages</th>
                <th style="text-align:left; padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">php-via</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr style="border-block-end:1px solid var(--border);">
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Approach</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Code generator — CLI parses Go source, outputs routing &amp; auth glue</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Runtime framework — call <code>$via-&gt;page()</code>, <code>$c-&gt;signal()</code> directly</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-block-end:1px solid var(--border);">
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">State scoping</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Per-page / per-request only</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);"><strong>TAB / ROUTE / SESSION / GLOBAL + custom</strong> — built-in</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-block-end:1px solid var(--border);">
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Auth / CSRF</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Built-in: HMAC-SHA256 tokens, pluggable session backends</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Not built-in</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-block-end:1px solid var(--border);">
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Events</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Typed events + NATS broker — multi-instance friendly</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Scope-based broadcast — single-process only</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-block-end:1px solid var(--border);">
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Tooling</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Full CLI: <code>init</code>, <code>gen</code>, <code>watch</code>, <code>lint</code></td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">None — just <code>php app.php</code></td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-block-end:1px solid var(--border);">
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Components</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Struct embedding</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);"><code>$c-&gt;component()</code> — sub-contexts with isolated state &amp; signals</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Templating</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Templ (compiled, type-safe)</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Twig (familiar, flexible)</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <p><strong>When to choose Datapages:</strong> you need CSRF protection, typed auth, pluggable session backends, or multi-instance deployment via NATS. Go's type system and generated code give you compile-time safety and a mature CLI workflow.</p>
    <p><strong>When to choose php-via:</strong> you want to be productive in PHP immediately, need the scoped state system for real-time multiplayer features, and don't want a build step.</p>

    <h2 id="stario">php-via vs Stario</h2>
    <p>
        <a href="https://stario.dev" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Stario</a> (v2.0) is a Python 3.14+ async framework with Datastar integration.
        It follows a Go-style stateless handler pattern with a rich response-writer API.
    </p>

    <table style="width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:var(--font-size-0); margin-block:var(--size-5);">
        <thead>
            <tr style="border-block-end:2px solid var(--border);">
                <th style="text-align:left; padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Area</th>
                <th style="text-align:left; padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Stario</th>
                <th style="text-align:left; padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">php-via</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr style="border-block-end:1px solid var(--border);">
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">State model</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Stateless handlers — read from <code>c</code>, write to <code>w</code></td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Stateful contexts — live for the entire SSE connection</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-block-end:1px solid var(--border);">
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">State scoping</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">None — signals are per-request</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);"><strong>TAB / ROUTE / SESSION / GLOBAL + custom</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-block-end:1px solid var(--border);">
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Response API</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Rich: <code>w.html()</code>, <code>w.json()</code>, <code>w.redirect()</code>, cookies, compression</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Higher-level: <code>$c-&gt;sync()</code>, <code>$c-&gt;view()</code>, <code>$c-&gt;execScript()</code></td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-block-end:1px solid var(--border);">
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Routing</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Full HTTP methods, sub-routers, host routing, middleware</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);"><code>$via-&gt;page()</code> only — actions handle POST internally</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-block-end:1px solid var(--border);">
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Disconnect</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);"><code>w.alive()</code> async iterator exits on disconnect</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);"><code>$c-&gt;onDisconnect(fn)</code> callback</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Templating</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Python functions composing HTML elements</td>
                <td style="padding:var(--size-2) var(--size-3);">Twig template files</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <p><strong>When to choose Stario:</strong> you work in Python, need full HTTP method routing, middleware, rich response control (cookies, redirects, compression), or built-in request tracing.</p>
    <p><strong>When to choose php-via:</strong> you work in PHP, want the scoped state system for multiplayer features, and prefer Twig templates with a persistent context model.</p>

